- 'Garden of projects' refers to the database of issues;
- 'Blossomed with more than five petals of commentary' refers to issues that have more than 5 comments;
- 'Highest priority' refers to `priority_id = 1`;
- 'Open issues' refers to issues with a status of 'Open'.

- "garden of tasks" refers to the issues table where each issue is a task;
- "gardeners" refer to the users who are assigned issues;
- "tending to more than one plant" means users who have more than one issue assigned to them.

- 'knights' refers to users in the system;
- 'realm of project management' refers to the database or project environment;
- 'burdened with the most open quests' refers to having the highest number of open issues assigned to them.

- "bustling gardens" refers to projects with a high number of issues;
- "flowers planted" refers to issues;
- "bees visited" refers to comments on issues;
- "types of flowers" refers to issue types.

- 'on the verge of blooming' refers to issues with a status of 'Open';
- 'in the midst of their journey' refers to issues with a status of 'In Progress';
- 'highest, second, or third level of urgency' refers to priority IDs 1, 2, or 3.

- "blossomed with the most issues" refers to the projects with the highest number of issues;
- "average priority levels" refers to the average value of the priority IDs;
- "last time they were tended to" refers to the latest update date of the issues.

- 'Status' refers to the current state of an issue (e.g., Open, In Progress, Closed);
- 'Priority' indicates the importance level of the issue;
- 'Average issue ID' is calculated as the mean of all issue IDs within each project and priority group.

- "Garden of projects" refers to the collection of projects in the database;
- "Plots" refers to the individual projects;
- "Bees" refers to issues that have received a lot of comments;
- "Flowers" refers to the issues within each project;
- "Top 3 flowers" means the issues with the highest comment counts in each project.

- "resolution time" is calculated as the difference between the date the issue was closed and the date it was created, using Julian day numbers for accuracy;
- "average resolution time" is the mean time it takes to close issues in a project, considering only issues that have been closed;
- "total issues" refers to the total number of issues in a project, regardless of their status.

- "blossomed into conversations" refers to issues that have more than two comments;
- "petals" represent individual comments;
- "garden" represents an issue;
- "vibrant gardens" refers to issues with the highest number of comments.

- "brought back to life" refers to the issue being reopened after being closed;
- "phoenix rising from the ashes" is a metaphor for an issue being reopened multiple times;
- The query ranks issues based on the number of times they have transitioned from 'Closed' to 'Open' status;
- The top 10 issues with the highest reopen count are selected.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT status) AS distinct_status_count
FROM issues
WHERE status = 'Open' AND resolution = 'Unresolved';

SELECT AVG(julianday(updated_date) - julianday(created_date)) AS avg_resolution_time
FROM issues
WHERE status = 'Closed';

SELECT 
  (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM issues WHERE status = 'Open') - 
  (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM issues WHERE resolution = 'Fixed') AS open_vs_fixed_diff;
